k, Sussex, England":"Berwick, Sussex, England","Berwick, Dorset, England":"Berwick, Dorset, England"},"en":{"about 1082–16 June 1165":"about 1082–16 June 1165","1082–1165":"1082–1165","1103–1145":"1103–1145","1125–1201":"1125–1201","1060–Male":"1060–Deceased","1060–1106":"1060–1106","about 1082":"about 1082","1165":"1165","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1060":"1060","1082":"1082","1081":"1081","1106":"1106","1125":"1125","1103":"1103","1124":"1124","1201":"1201","1145":"1145","about 1106":"about 1106","about 1125":"about 1125","about 1145":"about 1145","16 June 1165":"16 June 1165","Beaminster, Dorset, England":"Beaminster, Dorset, England","Berwick, Sussex, England":"Berwick, Sussex, England","Berwick, Dorset, England":"Berwick, Dorset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Russell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish: of Norman origin, from Old French and Anglo-Norman French <i>r(o)ussel</i>, a diminutive of Old French <i>rous(e)</i> ‘red, reddish’, used either as a nickname for someone with red hair or a ruddy complexion, or as a personal name. Compare   Rouse  . This Norman name has been established in Ireland since the 12th century. It has been reinforced in Britain and Ireland by Huguenot bearers of the name <i>Roussel</i>, of the same Old French origin.","English: habitational name from any of several places called Rushall (Norfolk, Staffordshire, Wiltshire) or possibly sometimes from Rusthall in Speldhurst (Kent). Rushall in Staffordshire derives from Old English <i>rysc</i> ‘rush, rushes’ + <i>halh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’. Rushall in Norfolk derives from an uncertain first element + Old English <i>halh</i>. Rushall in Wiltshire derives from an Old English personal name <i>Rust</i> (genitive <i>Rustes</i>) + <i>halh</i>. Rusthall in Speldhurst (Kent) probably derives from Old English <i>rust</i> ‘rust, rust color’ + <i>wella</i> ‘well, spring, stream’, but with a change in the final element due to influence from Middle English, Old English <i>hall</i> ‘hall, residence’, perhaps referring to a nearby building.","Americanized form of German <b>Rüssel</b>, from a pet form of any of various personal names formed with the element <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’."],"variants":[{"name":"Russler","meanings":["German (<b>Rüssler</b>):","occupational name for a farmer, from an agent derivative of <i>rüsseln</i> ‘to shallow plow’.","variant of <b>Rüssel</b> (see   Russell   2)."]},{"name":"Rouse","meanings":["English: nickname for a person with red hair or a ruddy complexion, from Middle English, Anglo-Norman French <i>rous(e)</i> ‘red(-haired)’ (from Latin <i>russ(e)us</i>).","Americanized form of German   Raus  .","Walloon and northern French (<b>Rousé</b>): variant of <b>Rosé</b> (see   Rose  )."]},{"name":"Russel","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Russell  .","German: from a pet form of <i>Russ</i>, see   Russ   2.","northwest German (<b>Rüssel</b>): probably a variant of   Rossel  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Informal short form of   Desmond ."],"variants":[{"name":"Desmond","meanings":["Transferred use of an Irish surname derived from the Gaelic byname <i>Deasmhumhnach</i> ‘(man from) south Munster’, an ancient Irish kingdom named after <i>Mumhu</i>, one of its early kings."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":4,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":14,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":24,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert de Russell I was born about 1082, in Berwick, Dorset, England, his father, Hugh de Russell II, was 24 and his mother, Matilda de Boves, was 24. He married Lady Jane in 1124, in Berwick, Sussex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 16 June 1165, in his hometown, at the age of 84."},"et":{"about 1082–16 June 1165":"umbes 1082–16. juuni 1165","1082–1165":"1082–1165","1103–11